  <h1>Open Action&rarr;Outcome Datasets</h1>
  <p class="tagline">Real-world reference points for testing models that predict the effects of decisions &mdash;
     each a real institutional decision, with the true effect recovered by a transparent quasi-experimental design
     (regression discontinuity &amp; kink, difference-in-differences, or controlled interrupted time series).</p>
  <div class="cta">
    <a class="btn" href="downloads.html">Get the data</a>
    <a class="btn secondary" href="schema.html">Read the schema</a>
    <a class="btn secondary" href="{{.RepoURL}}">View on GitHub</a>
  </div>
</section>

<h2>What's in it</h2>
<p>Two datasets, normalised on <code>mark_id</code>:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Marks</strong> &mdash; the reference points (the metadata). One small JSON per decision: the setup,
      the effect as an honest distribution, the validity evidence it passed, and full provenance.</li>
  <li><strong><code>episodes</code> dataset</strong> &mdash; the rows behind every mark as the
      <em>(state, action, reward)</em> view for model training. Published per mark (one gzipped CSV each), joined back to each mark on <code>mark_id</code>.</li>
</ul>
<p>You can check two things against a mark: does your model get the <strong>effect</strong> right, and is its <strong>confidence</strong> honest?</p>

<h2>Designs</h2>
<p>A mark is <strong>identification-agnostic</strong> &mdash; the effect distribution, the uncertainty budget, and the
   scorer are the same however comparability was established. Only the design block and the validity dossier change
   shape across the four supported quasi-experimental families:</p>
<div class="table-wrap">
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Design</th><th>Comparability from</th><th>Estimand</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>RDD</strong> &mdash; regression discontinuity (sharp / fuzzy)</td><td>Units just either side of a published cutoff</td><td>Local effect at the cutoff</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>RKD</strong> &mdash; regression-kink design</td><td>A change in the slope of a continuous policy function at a kink</td><td>Marginal effect of policy intensity</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>DiD</strong> &mdash; difference-in-differences</td><td>A treated group&rsquo;s pre&rarr;post change vs a control group&rsquo;s, under parallel trends</td><td>Average effect on the treated</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>ITS</strong> &mdash; controlled interrupted time series</td><td>A treated series&rsquo; break at a sharp intervention instant vs a control series sharing its pre-trend</td><td>Population effect over the post window</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p>Decision scores are compared <em>within</em> a design family, never pooled across; calibration scores are
   comparable everywhere. The <a href="schema.html">schema</a> documents the per-family fields.</p>

