<h2>The finding it's built to show</h2>
<p>A method that reports only its <em>sampling</em> error looks confident but is wrong too often &mdash; it ignores
   how much the answer depends on modelling choices. A method that accounts for that is honestly less certain, and
   better calibrated. In the committed calibration study, at a nominal 95% interval the plug-in method covers the
   truth only <strong>{{.PlugInCov}}</strong> of the time; the model-averaged method <strong>{{.SBICov}}</strong>.</p>
